- "literary gems" refers to books;
- "gained the admiration of at least three critics" means the book has at least 3 reviews;
- "shining with an average rating that surpasses the four-star mark" means the average rating is greater than 4.

- "Blossomed in popularity" refers to books with an average rating greater than 3;
- "Embraced by readers" refers to books that have been borrowed at least once;
- "Currently available for borrowing" refers to books where the `active` column is set to 1.

- "embraced by the readers" refers to books with at least one review;
- "average ratings" are calculated from the ratings given by users, typically on a scale of 1 to 5;
- "most beloved to the least" implies the results are ordered by average rating in descending order.

- "Most beloved" refers to books with the highest average ratings;
- "Wise scribes" refers to the authors of the books;
- "Literary treasures" refers to the books in the library;
- "Considering only those works that have been borrowed at least once" means the books must have a record in the `borrowings` table;
- "Have received at least one review" means the books must have at least one entry in the `book_reviews` table.

- "Borrowed at least once" means the book has a borrowing count greater than 0;
- "Average rating" is the mean of all ratings given by users for a book;
- "Edition count" is the number of different editions of a book;
- "Translation count" is the number of different translations of a book.

- The `author_books` table links authors to the books they have written;
- The `book_reviews` table contains user ratings for books;
- The query focuses on authors who have written multiple books and their overall reception in terms of average ratings.

- "shining star" refers to the category that stands out due to the book within it having the highest average review rating;
- "most beloved book" refers to the book with the highest average review rating;
- The hierarchy of categories is considered, starting from the top-level categories down to the subcategories.
